We've known for decades that rapid climate change is being caused by the release of greenhouse

00:23.920 --> 00:31.520
gases. But instead of reducing them, in 2019 the world was emitting 50% more CO2 than in

00:31.520 --> 00:39.400
the year 2000. And emissions are still rising. Why is that? Why is it so hard to just stop

00:39.400 --> 00:50.080
emitting these gases?

00:50.080 --> 00:55.200
Our collective CO2 emissions can be expressed as a product of four factors and their relationship

00:55.200 --> 01:01.960
with each other. Two of them explain why worldwide CO2 emissions are still rising, and two explain

01:01.960 --> 01:09.980
how we can stop that. Population size, economic growth, energy intensity, and emissions per

01:09.980 --> 01:19.880
energy unit produced. Number one, population size. People need food, homes, and clothing.

01:19.880 --> 01:26.720
And they demand luxury products from iPhones to $1 cheeseburgers. More people, higher CO2

01:26.720 --> 01:32.120
emissions. It's a very simple equation. The global population is growing, and according

01:32.120 --> 01:40.160
to the UN, it will level off at about 11 billion in 2100, which is 40% more than today. The

01:40.160 --> 01:45.080
only way to slow down this growth is investment in healthcare and access to contraception

01:45.080 --> 01:50.780
and education in developing countries. But even with massive investment, it will take

01:50.780 --> 01:55.960
a few decades for the effects of lower birth rates to manifest themselves. So the global

01:55.960 --> 02:01.920
population will keep growing for the foreseeable future, and as a consequence, global CO2 emissions

02:01.920 --> 02:09.720
will rise over the next few decades. Number two, growth or getting richer. But it's not

02:09.720 --> 02:15.920
just about our numbers. The richer and more developed we are, the more emissions our lifestyle

02:15.920 --> 02:23.440
produces. A programmer in the US has a higher CO2 footprint than 50 farmers in Uganda. The

02:23.440 --> 02:29.480
world's wealth is growing almost everywhere. And although it's far from evenly distributed,

02:29.480 --> 02:33.920
economic growth has led to the highest standards of living and the largest reduction in extreme

02:33.920 --> 02:40.400
poverty in human history. Growth has become the dominant mantra of the world's economies,

02:40.400 --> 02:46.520
no matter what kind of political system they have. It's unlikely that rich countries will give up the

02:46.520 --> 02:52.720
concept of growth anytime soon. But even if they were to, developing countries want to become rich

02:52.720 --> 02:59.400
too. For billions of people, the end of growth would probably mean staying poor, and so developing

02:59.400 --> 03:04.720
countries are not willing to stop growing their economies. All in all, we can be sure that growth

03:04.720 --> 03:11.400
as a guiding economic ideology is not going to go away anytime soon. More countries and their

03:11.400 --> 03:16.640
citizens around the world will grow and become richer, while the rich economies will continue

03:16.640 --> 03:22.360
to grow their wealth. There are some signs that growth can be decoupled from CO2 emissions,

03:22.360 --> 03:28.280
but we're not close to that yet. As a consequence of this growth, CO2 emissions will rise.

03:28.280 --> 03:33.320
Okay, so far we've learned that because of population growth and economic growth,

03:33.320 --> 03:40.560
humanity's CO2 emissions will increase, which is the opposite of what should be happening. We need

03:40.560 --> 03:47.760
to slow, peak, and then reduce annual emissions. The next two factors describe how we can actually

03:47.760 --> 03:56.240
do this. Number three, energy intensity. Energy intensity describes how efficiently we use energy.

03:56.280 --> 04:02.360
A street food vendor in rural Brazil might burn coal to cook, while a street food vendor in France

04:02.360 --> 04:09.360
might use an induction stove powered by nuclear energy. The latter is way more efficient. The

04:09.360 --> 04:15.280
more efficient something is, the less energy we need to do something, be it powering a metropolitan

04:15.280 --> 04:21.480
area or grilling a kebab. So making our technology more efficient and coming up with more efficient

04:21.480 --> 04:27.120
ways to organize our societies is one of the most important ways to reduce the modern world's CO2

04:27.120 --> 04:33.800
dependency. This can mean everything from reducing power consumption with AI, the electrification of

04:33.800 --> 04:39.920
the transportation and industrial sectors, or sustainable concrete production. The opportunities

04:39.920 --> 04:47.280
for improvement are almost limitless and human ingenuity can run wild. But we know that increasing

04:47.320 --> 04:55.800
efficiency alone will not be enough, mostly for three reasons. One, direct rebound effects. This

04:55.800 --> 05:01.160
means that once something becomes more efficient, it's used more and so overall the increased

05:01.160 --> 05:06.680
efficiency does not lead to a reduction as impressive as you would first think. Or worse,

05:06.680 --> 05:13.680
sometimes more efficiency makes humans not use less of a resource, but more of it. When planes

05:13.800 --> 05:20.080
became more fuel efficient, ticket prices decreased and more people started to travel by plane. So

05:20.080 --> 05:26.840
making things more efficient does not automatically mean less energy use in total. It might have the

05:26.840 --> 05:34.320
opposite effect. Two, indirect rebound effects. Sometimes when you save money on a thing that's

05:34.320 --> 05:38.720
become more efficient, you might spend it elsewhere. For example, if you buy a more

05:38.720 --> 05:44.320
fuel efficient car, you save money on fuel and end up with extra funds in your bank account that

05:44.320 --> 05:50.080
you might spend on a vacation and take a flight with. So in the end, you might actually emit more

05:50.080 --> 05:58.520
